Now I can see that @orpc DOES validate output! The `validateOutput` function:```javascript
async function validateOutput(procedure, output) {
  const schema = procedure["~orpc"].outputSchema;  if (!schema) {    return output;
  }
  const result = await schema["~standard"].validate(output);
  if (result.issues) {
    throw new ORPCError("INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR", {
      message: "Output validation failed",
      ...    });
  }
  return result.value;}```

So @orpc validates the output against the schema. If validation fails, it throws an `ORPCError("INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR")`.


The validation uses the standard-schema interface that Zod implements, which would check each array item and its fields against their schemas. Since `z.number()` would reject string values, if ClickHouse returns UInt64 as strings, the validation would fail and throw an error. But then the trends query works despite having the same `z.number()` fields, so something's different there. I need to investigate whether the `@clickhouse/client-web` library has a setting that controls how it formats 64-bit integers in JSON responses.

